"""
MKT Original Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 7–8 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-1chronicles-7-8-fill.py

Fills 78 missing verses (ch7 all except v23; ch8 all except v33).

Key decisions:
- Ch7 genealogy covers Issachar, Benjamin (first version), Dan fragment,
  Naphtali, Manasseh, Ephraim, Asher — each with military census totals
- v12 treated as a Dan fragment embedded in Benjamin section (Hushim = Dan's son)
- v24: Sheerah the city-builder — only woman credited with founding cities in OT
- v27: Joshua traced genealogically through Ephraim
- Ch8 is Benjamin's second extended genealogy with Saul family focus
- v8-10: Shaharaim's Moabite family — a private narrative unique to Chronicles
- v12: Shemed builds Ono and Lod (post-exilic Benjaminite settlement towns)
- v33-34 already present (Saul's sons with original theophoric Eshbaal/Merib-baal names)
"""

import json, os, sys

def load_comm(layer, book):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    if os.path.exists(path):
        with open(path) as f:
            return json.load(f)
    return {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    path = f'data/commentary/mkt-{layer}/{book}.json'
    os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(path), exist_ok=True)
    with open(path, 'w') as f:
        json.dump(data, f, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None)
    print(f'wrote {path}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, text in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = text

CHRONICLES = {
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>Issachar&rsquo;s four sons (Tola, Puah, Jashub, Shimron) match Gen 46:13 and Num 26:23&ndash;25 almost exactly, confirming a stable Issacharite list. The Chronicler&rsquo;s enumeration formula &ldquo;four in all&rdquo; (<em>ʾarbaʿāh</em>) is a recurring counting-close that marks the end of a first-generation list and sets up the descendant expansion that follows.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Tola&rsquo;s six sons are introduced as <em>rāʾšê lᵉḇêt ʾăḇôtām</em> (heads of their ancestral houses), placing this genealogy within the military-administrative register of the Chronicler. The figure of 22,600 warriors in David&rsquo;s day contrasts with Num 26:25 which gives 64,300 for Moses&rsquo; time; the reduction may reflect actual demographic change, or divergent source traditions. <em>Tôlᵉḏôtām</em> (&lsquo;their generations&rsquo;) signals the Chronicler&rsquo;s characteristic mode: genealogy and time-marking together.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Izrahiah&rsquo;s five sons are all &ldquo;leaders&rdquo; (<em>rāʾšîm</em>). The explicit count (&ldquo;five&rdquo;) is unusual for a sub-list and signals that all five sons have equal standing as heads &mdash; no hierarchy among them. Izrahiah&rsquo;s name means &lsquo;YHWH shines forth&rsquo; (<em>yizraḥyāh</em>), a theophoric name that establishes an Issacharite lineage with explicit YHWH-devotion.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Thirty-six thousand troops &ldquo;ready for war&rdquo; (<em>ʾanšê milḥāmāh</em>) attached to Izrahiah&rsquo;s sons; the reason given is &ldquo;for they had many wives and sons.&rdquo; The genealogical logic is demographic: many wives produce many sons, many sons produce large war-bands. The Chronicler&rsquo;s genealogies function simultaneously as population registers and military census documents &mdash; a dual purpose inherited from Numbers&rsquo; tribal counts.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The phrase <em>ʿal-kol-hityaḥaś</em> (according to all the genealogical enrollment) is diagnostic of the Chronicler&rsquo;s vocabulary: the root <em>yāḥaś</em> (to enroll in the genealogy) appears almost exclusively in Chronicles and Ezra-Nehemiah, reflecting the post-exilic concern with documented lineage as the basis for land-rights and temple participation. The grand total of 87,000 Issacharite warriors establishes the tribe as one of the most militarily significant in the Davidic census tradition.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Benjamin&rsquo;s three sons here (Bela, Becher, Jediael) diverge from both Gen 46:21 (ten sons) and Num 26:38&ndash;40 (Bela, Ashbel, Ahiram, Shupham, Hupham, five). The Chronicler is drawing on a different Benjaminite source, possibly a tribal register compiled under different administrative conditions. The variation in Benjaminite genealogy across the Pentateuch and Chronicles is one of the most complex source-critical puzzles in the Hebrew genealogical tradition.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Bela&rsquo;s five sons include Iri (whose sons Shuppim and Huppim appear in v12). <em>Gibbôrê ḥayil</em> (mighty warriors) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard honorific for genealogical line-holders who are simultaneously clan-heads and soldiers. The count of 22,034 for Bela&rsquo;s line situates this within the David-era military assessment framework established throughout ch7.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Becher&rsquo;s nine sons include Anathoth &mdash; the place-name later attached to Jeremiah&rsquo;s home village (Jer 1:1) and to one of the Levitical cities in Benjamin (Josh 21:18). The embedding of a place-name as a personal name suggests the Chronicler is recording a clan-founder: Becher&rsquo;s son Anathoth was the ancestor who settled the town of Anathoth. The genealogical enrollment of Becher&rsquo;s household is 20,200 mighty warriors.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The <em>hityaḥaśām</em> formula closes the Becher section, confirming 20,200 warriors. The Chronicler uses the reflexive Hithpael of <em>yāḥaś</em> to indicate self-registration in the genealogical record &mdash; a legal act of claiming membership in a tribe through documented enrollment, not simply birth-right. This implies that the tribal registers the Chronicler used were official administrative documents, not merely oral traditions.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jediael&rsquo;s son Bilhan has seven sons, the last being Ahishahar. The name Bilhan recalls the Horite clan leader of Gen 36:27 &mdash; a Edomite/Horite name appearing in Benjaminite genealogy, suggesting either name-borrowing across boundaries or historical intermarriage. Bilhan&rsquo;s seven sons all serve as military commanders, continuing the administrative-register character of the chapter.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Jediael&rsquo;s military total is 17,200, described as <em>ṣōʾê ṣāḇāʾ lammilḥāmāh</em> (those fit for going out to the army for battle) &mdash; a precise conscription formula. The three Benjaminite sub-lists (Bela, Becher, Jediael) together yield a massive northern Benjaminite warrior pool, anchoring Benjamin&rsquo;s military prominence before the Saul narrative that follows later in the book.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Shuppim and Huppim are here sons of Ir (a Benjaminite name); yet the identical pair appears in Num 26:39 as Benjaminite clans and in Gen 46:21 as Benjaminite sons. The second part of v12 &mdash; &ldquo;Hushim was the son of Aher&rdquo; &mdash; is widely recognized as a displaced Dan fragment. In Gen 46:23, Hushim is the only listed son of Dan; <em>ʾaḥēr</em> (&lsquo;another&rsquo;) may be a scribal placeholder for a damaged or omitted name (Dan), explaining why Dan is absent from the tribal genealogy list in ch7. The verse is textually problematic; the LXX and Syriac offer divergent readings.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Naphtali&rsquo;s four sons (Jahziel, Guni, Jezer, Shallum) nearly match Gen 46:24 (Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, Shillem) and Num 26:48&ndash;49; only &lsquo;Shallum&rsquo; vs. &lsquo;Shillem&rsquo; differs. The brief notation &ldquo;from Bilhah&rdquo; (<em>bᵉnê bîlhāh</em>) anchors Naphtali in the matrilineal tradition: both Dan and Naphtali were born to Jacob&rsquo;s concubine Bilhah (Gen 30:7&ndash;8). The Chronicler does not explain the tradition; the parentage note links the text to Genesis for readers who know the narrative.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Manasseh&rsquo;s genealogy through his Aramean concubine (<em>pîlegšô hāʾarammît</em>) reflects the historical and geographical reality of Gilead: Transjordanian Manasseh bordered Aram and shows evidence of substantial Aramean intermarriage in its population. Machir, Manasseh&rsquo;s firstborn, was the father of Gilead &mdash; a territorial eponym: the region of Gilead takes its name from this genealogical ancestor (Num 26:29; Josh 17:1).</p>",
    "15": "<p>Machir takes wives for Huppim and Shuppim &mdash; the same names as the Benjaminite clan of v12, now appearing as women (or as male recipients of wives). The MT is syntactically difficult and translators disagree; some read &ldquo;Huppim and Shuppim&rdquo; as the names of Machir&rsquo;s wives rather than as men for whom he obtained wives. His sister Maachah becomes his wife in some readings (endogamous marriage). The mention of Zelophehad who &ldquo;had only daughters&rdquo; connects to the landmark Num 27 case where Zelophehad&rsquo;s daughters successfully petitioned for inheritance rights in the absence of male heirs.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Maachah bears Peresh (&lsquo;horseman&rsquo;?) and Sheresh (&lsquo;root&rsquo;); Sheresh&rsquo;s sons are Ulam and Rakem. These names are not attested elsewhere in this genealogical combination. The repeated matrilineal focus (which woman bore which son) in the Manasseh genealogy is unusual and may reflect source material that preserved women&rsquo;s names because inheritance passed through named female lines (cf. the Zelophehad daughters&rsquo; precedent, Num 27).</p>",
    "17": "<p>Ulam&rsquo;s son Bedan completes the Gilead sub-line: Manasseh &rarr; Machir &rarr; Gilead &rarr; Ulam &rarr; Bedan. Bedan appears also as a judge in 1 Sam 12:11 (where some manuscripts read Barak); this may be a different Bedan, or a tradition identifying a Manassite war-leader with a judge&rsquo;s career. The nested genealogical formula &ldquo;son of Gilead son of Machir son of Manasseh&rdquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s way of establishing deep pedigree legitimacy for each sub-line.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Hammoleketh (&lsquo;the queen&rsquo;; also spelled Hammolecheth) bears Ishhod, Abiezer, and Mahalah. Whether &ldquo;hammoleketh&rdquo; is a proper name or a title is debated; it could denote a woman who exercised royal or clan-leadership in Manasseh. Abiezer of Manasseh is the clan of Gideon (Judg 6:11, 24, 34) &mdash; this genealogical note therefore traces the great judge of the Midianite period to a named ancestral line within Manasseh through a woman whose name means &lsquo;the queen.&rsquo;</p>",
    "19": "<p>Shemida&rsquo;s four sons (Ahian, Shechem, Likhi, Aniam) are otherwise unattested beyond Num 26:32 where Shemida is listed as a Manassite clan. Shechem as a personal name in Manasseh is historically plausible: Shechem (the city) was within Manassite territory and may have had Manassite clan associations before it became a Levitical city (Josh 21:21). The names in this sub-list have no parallels elsewhere, suggesting the Chronicler had access to a distinct Manassite administrative source.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ephraim&rsquo;s linear descent (Shuthelah &rarr; Bered &rarr; Tahath &rarr; Eladah &rarr; Tahath) is a segmented genealogy condensed into a linear form. The repeated name Tahath (two different men) reflects the practice of naming sons after grandfathers; the Chronicler or his source is careful to distinguish them by their position in the sequence. Shuthelah appears in Num 26:35&ndash;36 as an Ephraimite clan with its own sub-clans, confirming the antiquity of this line.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Ezer and Elead are killed by the men of Gath while raiding their herds. This is a narrative fragment embedded in the genealogy, with no parallel in any other biblical text. The phrase &ldquo;because they came down to take their herds&rdquo; (<em>kî yārᵉḏû lāqaḥat ʾet miqnêhem</em>) clarifies that the Ephraimites were the aggressors in a cattle raid; the Gittites&rsquo; counter-attack was a legitimate reprisal. The episode functions etiologically: it explains a gap in the Ephraimite genealogical line and accounts for a tradition of Ephraimite-Philistine hostility predating the main settlement period.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ephraim&rsquo;s extended mourning (&ldquo;many days,&rdquo; <em>yāmîm rabbîm</em>) and his brothers&rsquo; consolation (<em>nāḥam</em> Piel) are rare emotional notes in a genealogical list. The Piel of <em>nāḥam</em> is the same root used when Jacob&rsquo;s sons attempt to comfort him after Joseph&rsquo;s apparent death (Gen 37:35, where their comfort fails) and when Job&rsquo;s friends come to comfort him (Job 2:11). The parallel with Jacob&rsquo;s grief over a lost son is striking: in both cases, a patriarch mourns the loss of the generation below him; in both cases, the story continues despite the grief.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Sheerah (<em>šᵉʾērāh</em>, &lsquo;female relative&rsquo; or a personal name from the root <em>šʾr</em>, remainder/kin) is the only woman in the Hebrew Bible explicitly credited with founding and building cities. She built Lower Beth-horon, Upper Beth-horon, and Uzzen-sheerah. Beth-horon (upper and lower) guarded the principal descent from the Benjaminite-Ephraimite highlands to the Aijalon plain and the coast; Joshua pursued the Amorite coalition through this pass (Josh 10:10&ndash;11). The third city, Uzzen-sheerah (<em>ʾuzzên šᵉʾērāh</em>, &lsquo;ear/attentiveness of Sheerah&rsquo;), memorializes her name in geography &mdash; a permanent monument in the landscape. The Chronicler preserves this tradition without comment or qualification, treating a woman&rsquo;s city-founding as genealogically significant heritage.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Rephah and Resheph begin the linear descent from Ephraim toward Joshua. These names are otherwise unattested in this context; <em>rešep</em> is also the name of a Canaanite deity (fire/plague), but personal theophoric names involving Resheph appear in Egyptian documents from the New Kingdom period for Canaanite-Semitic individuals. The line passes through Tahan, Ladan, and then Ammihud.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Ladan &rarr; Ammihud &rarr; Elishama. Elishama was the tribal leader of Ephraim in the wilderness census (Num 1:10; 2:18; 7:48&ndash;53; 10:22) and the grandfather of Joshua in the genealogy the Chronicler is building. The Chronicler is providing Joshua with documented genealogical roots seven generations deep from Ephraim, grounding the military saviour of the conquest in a legitimate administrative lineage.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Elishama &rarr; Non &rarr; Joshua (<em>yᵉhôšûaʿ</em>, &lsquo;YHWH saves/is salvation&rsquo;). This is the only place in the Chronicler&rsquo;s work where Joshua receives an explicit genealogy connecting him to Ephraim through named ancestors. The name <em>yᵉhôšûaʿ</em> is theophoric: the <em>yᵉhô-</em> prefix is the divine name and <em>-šûaʿ</em> is from the root <em>yšʿ</em> (to save, deliver). Moses renamed Hoshea (<em>hôšēaʿ</em>) to Yehoshua (Num 13:16) &mdash; the added theophoric element transforms &lsquo;salvation&rsquo; into &lsquo;YHWH is salvation.&rsquo; The name prefigures his role as the instrument of YHWH&rsquo;s deliverance of Israel into the land.</p>",
    "28": "<p>Ephraim&rsquo;s territorial inventory includes Bethel, Naaran, Gezer, Shechem, and Ayyah. Bethel, the site of Jacob&rsquo;s vision (Gen 28:10&ndash;22) and later Jeroboam&rsquo;s golden calf (1 Kgs 12:29), is here anchored in Ephraimite genealogical tradition as rightful Ephraimite territory. Gezer, a key Canaanite city-state in the Shephelah, was given to Solomon as a dowry (1 Kgs 9:16); its inclusion in an Ephraimite territorial list reflects the tribal claim that preceded the Solomonic arrangement. The territorial inventory follows Josh 16 closely.</p>",
    "29": "<p>Manasseh&rsquo;s border cities &mdash; Beth-shean, Taanach, Megiddo, Dor &mdash; are precisely the cities that Manasseh failed to drive out in the early settlement period (Josh 17:11&ndash;13; Judg 1:27&ndash;28). The Chronicler&rsquo;s inventory follows the same list as Joshua, preserving the historical record of the contested border. The closing phrase &ldquo;these are the sons of Joseph son of Israel&rdquo; brackets the entire Joseph-tribal section (Manasseh and Ephraim in ch7:14&ndash;29) under the Joseph patronymic, reflecting the Chronicler&rsquo;s awareness that the two tribes constituted Joseph&rsquo;s double-portion inheritance.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Asher&rsquo;s sons (Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, Beriah, and sister Serah) match Gen 46:17 and Num 26:44&ndash;46 closely. Serah (<em>seraḥ</em>) is remarkable: a woman named across three distinct genealogical passages (Gen 46:17; Num 26:46; 1 Chr 7:30), an unusual longevity of tradition for a female ancestor. Post-biblical tradition identified Serah bat Asher as an immortal elder-woman who survived from the patriarchal period into the exodus &mdash; a midrashic elaboration of her unusual genealogical prominence.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Beriah&rsquo;s sons are Heber and Malchiel; Malchiel is the &ldquo;father of Birzaith&rdquo; &mdash; another city-founding genealogical note (cf. Sheerah v24; Shemed v12 of ch8). <em>bîrzayit</em> may be an olive-oil town (the root <em>zayit</em> = olive). Heber&rsquo;s descendants are extended further in vv32&ndash;39, making Heber&rsquo;s line the main Asherite genealogical focus.</p>",
    "32": "<p>Heber fathers Japhlet, Shomer, Hotham, and their sister Shua. The inclusion of another named sister (Shua) mirrors the inclusion of Serah (v30); the Asherite genealogy preserves two generations of named women within the tribal register, which is rare. Shua appears elsewhere only as the name of Judah&rsquo;s Canaanite wife (Gen 38:2), so the name crossed tribal boundaries.</p>",
    "33": "<p>Japhlet&rsquo;s three sons (Pasach, Bimhal, Ashvath) are otherwise unattested. The name Japhlet echoes Japhlet&rsquo;s border in Josh 16:3, possibly marking a Japhletite clan that held territory on the Ephraimite-Asherite border. None of the three sons have cognates in the surrounding lists.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Shomer&rsquo;s sons include Ahi and Aram. The name Aram as a personal name in an Asherite genealogy is notable: Asher&rsquo;s territory in the far north (coastal Galilee) bordered Aramean territory and showed Aramean cultural contact. The names in this sub-section are without parallel; the Chronicler is preserving source material that has no Pentateuchal correlate.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Helem (possibly another name for Hotham of v32 &mdash; the same name in slightly different vocalization) heads a four-son sub-list: Zophah, Imna, Shelesh, Amal. The uncertainty over Helem/Hotham identity is a typical feature of Chronicles&rsquo; genealogies where scribal transmission occasionally introduces name variants for the same individual.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Zophah&rsquo;s six sons, beginning with Suah (possibly &lsquo;sweeping away&rsquo;) and Harnepher. Several names in this list appear to be of non-Semitic or mixed origin, consistent with Asher&rsquo;s northern coastal location where Phoenician, Hurrian, and Canaanite naming conventions overlapped with Israelite ones.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The second half of Zophah&rsquo;s sons: Bezer, Hod, Shamma, Shilshah, Ithran, and Beera. Bezer appears also as a city of refuge east of the Jordan (Deut 4:43; Josh 20:8); personal names and place-names frequently overlap in tribal genealogies because clan-founders named sites after themselves or vice versa. Ithran appears in a Horite genealogy (Gen 36:26) &mdash; another instance of a name crossing the Israelite-Edomite boundary.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Jether&rsquo;s three sons: Jephunneh, Pispa, and Ara. Jephunneh is the name of Caleb&rsquo;s father (Num 13:6), a famous Judahite; its appearance as an Asherite sub-clan head suggests either name-borrowing or a genuine genealogical overlap between the two tribes in the Negev-coastal region. Ara (perhaps from Aramaic/North Semitic) continues the pattern of names with possible non-Israelite origins in Asher&rsquo;s genealogy.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Ulla&rsquo;s three sons: Arah, Hanniel, Rizia. Arah appears in Ezra-Nehemiah as a returnee family name (Ezra 2:5; Neh 7:10), suggesting that the Asherite genealogy may have been used in the post-exilic period to verify the tribal credentials of families claiming Asherite origin. The Chronicler&rsquo;s compilation thus served a living community function: establishing who belonged to which tribe for the purposes of land-allocation and cultic participation after the return from Babylon.</p>",
    "40": "<p>The Asher chapter closes with the military-census formula: &ldquo;All these were sons of Asher, heads of ancestral houses, chosen men, mighty warriors (<em>gibbôrê ḥayil</em>), outstanding leaders. Their genealogical enrollment as warriors ready for war numbered 26,000 men.&rdquo; The phrase <em>rāʾšê hᵉnāśîʾîm</em> (heads of the rulers/leaders) is unusually honorific. The 26,000 figure is the smallest of the tribal military totals in ch7, but the closing formula is the most elaborate, as if the Chronicler wanted to honor Asher&rsquo;s northern frontier position with heightened ceremonial language.</p>"
  },
  "8": {
    "1": "<p>Benjamin&rsquo;s sons in ch8 (Bela, Ashbel, Aharah, Nohah, Rapha) differ from Gen 46:21 (ten sons including Muppim, Huppim, Ard) and Num 26:38&ndash;40 (five with Ahiram, Shupham, Hupham). &ldquo;Aharah&rdquo; may be a scribal variant of &ldquo;Ahiram&rdquo; (transposition of consonants); &ldquo;Nohah&rdquo; and &ldquo;Rapha&rdquo; have no Pentateuchal parallel. The Chronicler is using a distinct Benjaminite source for ch8 &mdash; possibly a tribal register compiled independently of Genesis and Numbers &mdash; resulting in the two partially overlapping Benjaminite genealogies of ch7 and ch8.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The ordinal designations (firstborn, second, third, fourth, fifth) for Benjamin&rsquo;s five sons establish primogeniture order for the tribal genealogy. The ordinal series is unusual: the Chronicler normally lists names without rank, but here the ranking parallels the format used in Num 26:38&ndash;40 where Benjamin&rsquo;s sons are listed as &ldquo;after their families.&rdquo; The ordinal sequence anchors Bela as the genealogically primary line, which explains why Bela&rsquo;s descendants receive the most extensive treatment in what follows.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Bela&rsquo;s first three sons (Addar, Gera, Abihud) represent the first generation of the expansion. Gera is a recurring Benjaminite name: Ehud&rsquo;s father (Judg 3:15), Shimei&rsquo;s father (2 Sam 16:5), and here a clan in Bela&rsquo;s line. The name&rsquo;s repetition across generations and genealogical texts suggests it was a prestige clan name in Benjamin, recycled through multiple generations as a way of maintaining genealogical continuity with the founding ancestor.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Abishua, Naaman, and Ahoah continue Bela&rsquo;s list. Naaman (<em>nōʿamān</em>, &lsquo;pleasantness/grace&rsquo;) is notably the name of the Aramean general healed of leprosy by Elisha (2 Kgs 5:1) &mdash; the same name in a Benjaminite tribal context confirms it was an Israelite as well as Aramean name. Naaman also appears in Num 26:40 as a Benjaminite clan, consistent with this genealogy&rsquo;s overlap with Numbers.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Gera, Shephuphan, and Huram close Bela&rsquo;s first sub-list. The second Gera in this list (v5 vs. v3) is either a second son named Gera or a textual error; the Chronicler&rsquo;s tolerance for repeated personal names within the same family reflects actual ancient naming practice (naming after grandfathers). Shephuphan is a variant of Shupham/Muppim from Genesis and Numbers, confirming this list is partly parallel to and partly divergent from the Pentateuchal sources.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The sons of Ehud (<em>ʾēhûḏ</em>) &mdash; the famous left-handed judge (Judg 3:15) was a Benjaminite, son of Gera. Here Ehud&rsquo;s descendants are identified as &ldquo;heads of ancestral houses of the inhabitants of Geba.&rdquo; Geba was a Benjaminite priestly city on the border with the Philistines (1 Sam 13:3, 16). The exile to Manahath (<em>wayyigᵉlûm ʾel mᵉnaḥat</em>) is otherwise unattested; Manahath is a Calebite place in the Shephelah (2:52, 54), suggesting an intra-tribal movement rather than a foreign exile.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Naaman, Ahijah, and Gera; &ldquo;he removed them&rdquo; (<em>hûʾ higᵉlām</em>) &mdash; the antecedent of &ldquo;he&rdquo; is syntactically ambiguous in the MT. Following the MT literally, Gera of Ehud&rsquo;s line is the one who &ldquo;removed them&rdquo; to Manahath &mdash; possibly a forced resettlement of part of the Ehudite sub-clan, perhaps for punishment or administrative reorganization. The verse then notes Gera &ldquo;fathered Uzza and Ahihud&rdquo; after the relocation, continuing the genealogy past the disruption. LXX and Syriac smooth the syntax differently.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Shaharaim (&lsquo;double dawn&rsquo; or &lsquo;the dawn-double&rsquo;) is an otherwise unattested figure whose personal story is entirely unique to Chronicles. He &ldquo;fathered children in the land of Moab after he had divorced his wives Hushim and Baara.&rdquo; The verb <em>šallaḥ</em> (to send away, Piel) is the technical term for divorce. The detail that a Benjaminite patriarch settled in Moab and started a second family there is remarkable; it creates an Israelite family tradition in Moab parallel to the Ruth narrative, though moving in the opposite direction.</p>",
    "9": "<p>By his new wife Hodesh (&lsquo;the new moon&rsquo; &mdash; a lunar theophoric name) Shaharaim fathers seven sons. Jobab appears elsewhere as an Edomite king (Gen 36:33&ndash;34) and a Canaanite city-king (Josh 11:1); the name was shared across ethnic groups in the southern Levant. Zibia (<em>ṣibyāʾ</em>, &lsquo;gazelle&rsquo;) is a feminine name in its more common form (2 Kgs 12:1), suggesting that male and female forms of animal names were used interchangeably in the naming tradition.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Jeuz, Sachia, and Mirmah close Hodesh&rsquo;s sons, designated &ldquo;heads of ancestral houses.&rdquo; Whatever the moral ambiguity of Shaharaim&rsquo;s marital history, his sons by Hodesh achieve the honorific <em>rāʾšê ʾābôt</em> (heads of fathers&rsquo; houses) &mdash; the Chronicler records genealogical legitimacy without editorial judgment on the patriarch&rsquo;s personal conduct. The genealogy reports; it does not adjudicate.</p>",
    "11": "<p>By his first wife Hushim, Shaharaim had also fathered Abitub and Elpaal before the divorce. Elpaal (&lsquo;God has performed&rsquo; or &lsquo;El works&rsquo;; <em>ʾel pāʿal</em>) becomes the primary genealogical line in vv12&ndash;18. The Chronicler tracks both sets of children from Shaharaim&rsquo;s divided household, preserving the parallel branches even though they originated from different mothers in different countries.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Elpaal&rsquo;s sons include Eber, Misham, and Shemed, with the editorial note that &ldquo;Shemed built Ono and Lod with its towns.&rdquo; Ono and Lod are in the Shephelah near the modern Tel Aviv coastal plain; Lod is present-day Lod/Lydda. These cities appear in Ezra 2:33 and Neh 11:35 as Benjaminite post-exilic settlement towns, so Shemed&rsquo;s city-founding establishes the genealogical claim to these sites that the returning community would have exercised after the Babylonian exile. The formula &ldquo;with its towns&rdquo; (<em>wᵉbᵉnōtêhā</em>) is the standard territorial formula for a city with dependent villages.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Beriah and Shema are &ldquo;heads of ancestral houses for the inhabitants of Aijalon, who drove out the inhabitants of Gath.&rdquo; The Aijalon valley was Joshua&rsquo;s battlefield (Josh 10:12); the connection to driving out Gath&rsquo;s inhabitants is historically puzzling, since Gath is a major Philistine city far to the southwest. This may refer to a local Gath-enclave within Benjaminite territory (several places bore the name Gath, meaning &lsquo;winepress&rsquo;) or to a Philistine outpost in the Aijalon region. The verb <em>bāraḥ</em> (Hiphil: to drive out) marks this as a victory claim embedded in the genealogy.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Ahio, Shashak, and Jeremoth are listed without sub-grouping here &mdash; their family attribution comes in the following verses. The name Ahio (<em>ʾaḥyô</em>, &lsquo;his brother&rsquo; or &lsquo;YHWH is my brother&rsquo;) is the same name as one of Abinadab&rsquo;s sons who accompanied the ark-cart (2 Sam 6:3&ndash;4); the Benjaminite context here differs from the Gittite-Judahite context there.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Zebadiah, Arad, and Eder are three more Benjaminite heads. Arad (<em>ʿărāḏ</em>) is best known as the Canaanite city in the Negev (Num 21:1; Josh 12:14); its use as a personal name may reflect family tradition connected to that region, or it may be an entirely independent naming. The multiplicity of names without stories in these lists reflects the reality of genealogical records: most ancestors leave only a name, not a narrative.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Michael, Ishpah, and Joha are identified as &ldquo;sons of Beriah&rdquo; (connecting back to v13). Michael (<em>mîkāʾēl</em>, &lsquo;who is like God?&rsquo;) is the most theologically freighted personal name in this list; the rhetorical question embedded in the name is a devotional formula asserting YHWH&rsquo;s incomparability (cf. Mic 7:18, <em>mî ʾēl kāmôkā</em>, &lsquo;who is a God like you?&rsquo;). The name appears for multiple individuals in Chronicles.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Zebadiah, Meshullam, Hizki, and Heber are &ldquo;sons of Elpaal.&rdquo; Meshullam (<em>mᵉšullām</em>, &lsquo;rewarded/repaid&rsquo; or &lsquo;at peace with God&rsquo;) is one of the most common names in Ezra-Nehemiah, reflecting its post-exilic popularity; its appearance in this pre-exilic Benjaminite list shows the name had an older history. Hizki (<em>ḥizqî</em>, &lsquo;my strength&rsquo; or &lsquo;YHWH is strength&rsquo;) is a shortened form of Hezekiah.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Ishmerai, Izliah, and Jobab close the sons of Elpaal. This section (vv17&ndash;18) provides nine sons for Elpaal across two verses, consistent with the Benjaminite pattern of large family clusters. Jobab appears here for the second time in ch8 (also v9), confirming its currency as a Benjaminite name at multiple genealogical levels.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Jakim, Zichri, and Zabdi are &ldquo;sons of Shimei.&rdquo; This Shimei is not identified further; multiple Shimeis appear in Chronicles and the surrounding biblical narrative (most famously David&rsquo;s curser, 2 Sam 16:5&ndash;13). The Benjaminite Shimei sub-clans here have no direct narrative connection to the famous Shimei. Zichri (<em>ziḵrî</em>, &lsquo;my memorial&rsquo; or from <em>zāḵar</em>, &lsquo;to remember&rsquo;) is a name asserting the parent&rsquo;s hope that the child will be remembered &mdash; ironically appropriate for a genealogical register.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Elienai, Zillethai, and Eliel are the second trio of Shimei&rsquo;s sons. Elienai (&lsquo;my eyes are toward God&rsquo;) and Eliel (&lsquo;God is my God&rsquo; or &lsquo;God, O God&rsquo;) are theophoric names expressing devotion to El/God. The density of <em>ʾēl</em>-element names in this section (Michael v16, Elienai, Eliel) reflects a post-exilic naming fashion that the Chronicler has recorded without comment.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Adaiah, Beraiah, and Shimrath close Shimei&rsquo;s sons. Adaiah (<em>ʿăḏāyāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH has adorned/testified&rsquo;) is a priestly name common in Ezra-Nehemiah (Ezra 10:29, 39; Neh 11:5, 12). Its appearance here in a Benjaminite warrior genealogy shows that names popular in the Levitical-priestly sphere also circulated in the lay tribal register. Shimrath (<em>šimrāt</em>, &lsquo;guarding&rsquo;) uses the same root as Shemer/Shamer, recurring Benjaminite-Asherite names.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Ishpan, Eber, and Eliel are sons of Shashak. Eber (<em>ʿēḇer</em>, the ancestral eponym of the Hebrews in Gen 10:21&ndash;25) appears here as a Benjaminite personal name; the same name occurs in Elpaal&rsquo;s list (v12). The repetition within ch8 of common names (Eber, Gera, Zichri, Eliel) across different sub-clans reflects either actual naming practice or the possibility that similar names in the sources were assigned to different branches in the compilation.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Abdon, Zichri, and Hanan &mdash; sons of Shashak (continuing the list from v22). Abdon is a judge&rsquo;s name (Judg 12:13&ndash;15) and a Levitical city in Asher (Josh 21:30); its appearance as a Benjaminite sub-clan head underscores that judge-names circulated across tribal boundaries. Hanan (<em>ḥānān</em>, &lsquo;gracious&rsquo;) is a common shortened form of various theophoric names (Hannah, Hananiah).</p>",
    "24": "<p>Hananiah, Elam, and Antothijah close Shashak&rsquo;s eleven sons (vv22&ndash;25). Hananiah (<em>ḥananyāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH is gracious&rsquo;) is one of the most common theophoric names in the Hebrew Bible and appears prominently in the Babylonian captivity narrative (the Hebrew name of Shadrach, Dan 1:6). Antothijah (&lsquo;answer of YHWH&rsquo; or &lsquo;supplications of YHWH&rsquo;) is a unique name in the Bible, possibly reflecting a family tradition of naming a child born in response to prayer.</p>",
    "25": "<p>Iphedeiah and Penuel close Shashak&rsquo;s sub-list. Penuel (<em>pᵉnûʾēl</em>, &lsquo;face of God&rsquo;) is the name Jacob gave to the site of his wrestling match with the angel (Gen 32:30); its use as a personal name takes the theophanic place-name into the private sphere. The two-name sub-list marks the end of Shashak&rsquo;s documented line, with eleven sons recorded in total across vv22&ndash;25.</p>",
    "26": "<p>Shamsherai, Shehariah, and Athaliah are sons of Jeroham. Athaliah (<em>ʿatalyhāh</em>) is best known as the name of the queen who seized Judahite power after Ahaziah&rsquo;s death (2 Kgs 11). Its appearance here as a masculine Benjaminite name is striking: the name was evidently gender-neutral, and the queen of Judah was named after a Benjaminite male ancestor. The name may derive from a root meaning &lsquo;YHWH is exalted&rsquo; or &lsquo;afflicted of YHWH.&rsquo;</p>",
    "27": "<p>Jaareshiah, Elijah, and Zichri close Jeroham&rsquo;s line. Elijah (<em>ʾēliyyāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH is my God&rsquo;) is the same name as the Tishbite prophet (1 Kgs 17:1). Its use as a Benjaminite personal name confirms that the name predated the famous prophet and was not an honorific coined for him. The three-name closing formula for Jeroham&rsquo;s sons echoes the three-name pattern used throughout this section of ch8.</p>",
    "28": "<p>&ldquo;These were heads of ancestral houses throughout their generations &mdash; leading men who lived in Jerusalem.&rdquo; The summary verse bridges the genealogical register to its geographic implication: these Benjaminite families are the established Jerusalem residents. The post-exilic context gives this note urgency: who has the legitimate claim to live in Jerusalem? The Chronicler answers by tracing Benjaminite Jerusalem residence to deep genealogical roots. Neh 11:7&ndash;9 provides a parallel list of Benjaminites in Jerusalem, confirming this demographic claim.</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;The father of Gibeon (<em>ʾăḇî giḇʿôn</em>) lived at Gibeon; his wife&rsquo;s name was Maachah.&rdquo; The formula &ldquo;father of [city-name]&rdquo; designates the clan-founder whose descendants settled and controlled that city. Gibeon is the Benjaminite town famous for the covenant with Joshua (Josh 9), the Gibeonite massacre under Saul (2 Sam 21:1&ndash;9), and Solomon&rsquo;s dream (1 Kgs 3:4&ndash;15). Its connection to the Saul genealogy that follows is direct: Saul&rsquo;s family was rooted in Gibeon, which explains Saul&rsquo;s culpability in the Gibeonite massacre.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Gibeon&rsquo;s patriarch&rsquo;s firstborn son was Abdon, followed by Zur, Kish, Baal, and Nadab. Kish will become Saul&rsquo;s father (v33) &mdash; here Kish is listed third among five brothers, establishing the modesty of Saul&rsquo;s pedigree (not from the firstborn line). Baal as a personal name in a YHWH-worshipping Israelite family poses the same interpretive challenge as Eshbaal in v33: the word <em>baʿal</em> means &lsquo;master/lord&rsquo; and was not necessarily polytheistic in early Israelite usage (cf. Hos 2:16&ndash;17).</p>",
    "31": "<p>Gedor, Ahio, and Zacher are additional sons of the Gibeon patriarch. Gedor as a personal name echoes the Judahite place-name Gedor (4:4, 18); again, geographic and personal names overlap. Ahio appears in 2 Sam 6:3&ndash;4 as one of the men who drove the ark-cart from Kirjath-jearim; whether this is the same Ahio or a coincidence of name is uncertain. Zacher is a shortened form of Zechariah (<em>zᵉḵaryāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH remembers&rsquo;).</p>",
    "32": "<p>Mikloth fathered Shimeah (<em>šimʿāh</em>, &lsquo;YHWH has heard&rsquo;); both &ldquo;also lived in Jerusalem, across from their kinsmen.&rdquo; The note of dual residence (Gibeon for the main family; Jerusalem for the Mikloth-Shimeah branch) reflects the reality that aristocratic families in tribal societies maintained households in multiple locations. The phrase &ldquo;across from their kinsmen&rdquo; (<em>negeḏ ʾᵃḥêhem</em>) suggests proximity without subordination: a branch family maintaining its identity in Jerusalem while acknowledging connection to the Gibeonite parent clan.</p>",
    "34": "<p>Jonathan&rsquo;s son was Meribbaal (<em>mᵉrîḇ baʿal</em>, &lsquo;Baal contends&rsquo; or &lsquo;Baal pleads [the cause]&rsquo;); Meribbaal fathered Micah. The parallel in 2 Sam 9 and 2 Sam 4:4 uses the Samuel editor&rsquo;s substituted form Mephibosheth (<em>mᵉpîḇōšet</em>). Micah, Jonathan&rsquo;s grandson, receives an extended genealogy in vv35&ndash;38, confirming that the Saul-Jonathan line continued into the post-monarchic period as a recognized Benjaminite family. The Chronicler&rsquo;s interest in preserving this line may reflect a post-exilic Saulide community that appealed to it for tribal standing.</p>",
    "35": "<p>Micah&rsquo;s four sons: Pithon, Melech, Tarea, and Ahaz. The naming of Micah&rsquo;s son Ahaz is notable: Ahaz is the Davidic king who later brought Judah into crisis by his Assyrian alliances and altar-substitution (2 Chr 28). The Benjaminite Ahaz here precedes the Davidic Ahaz chronologically and is a different individual; the coincidence of names across tribal lines underscores that personal names in this period were not uniquely assigned.</p>",
    "36": "<p>Ahaz &rarr; Jehoadah &rarr; Alemeth, Azmaveth, Zimri; Zimri &rarr; Moza. Azmaveth (<em>ʿazmāwet</em>, &lsquo;death is strong&rsquo; or &lsquo;strong as death&rsquo;) appears as a warrior in David&rsquo;s army (2 Sam 23:31) and as a place-name near Jerusalem (Neh 12:29); the name&rsquo;s military-mortuary meaning reflects the warrior ethos of the genealogy. Zimri is the name of the notorious Israelite king who killed Baasha&rsquo;s line and reigned for seven days (1 Kgs 16:9&ndash;20); the name was pre-existent as a personal name, not coined for the king.</p>",
    "37": "<p>Moza &rarr; Binea &rarr; Rapha &rarr; Eleasah &rarr; Azel. The deep genealogy of the Meribbaal-Micah line (six additional generations after Jonathan) anchors the Saulide family in a continuous genealogical record stretching from the Gibeon patriarch (v29) through Saul&rsquo;s grandchildren and beyond. The Chronicler&rsquo;s interest in this detail reflects either a living Saulide community in the post-exilic period or an archival fidelity to complete whatever genealogical sources he had.</p>",
    "38": "<p>Azel&rsquo;s six sons: Azrikam, Bocheru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan. The six sons &ldquo;all sons of Azel&rdquo; is an emphatic closing formula asserting that all six are legitimate, full sons and not step-children or servants. Obadiah (<em>ʿōḇaḏyāh</em>, &lsquo;servant of YHWH&rsquo;) and Ishmael (<em>yišmāʿēʾl</em>, &lsquo;God hears&rsquo;) are theophoric names attesting continued YHWH-devotion in the Saulide family well after the dynasty&rsquo;s end.</p>",
    "39": "<p>Azel&rsquo;s brother Eshek has three sons: Ulam (firstborn), Jeush (second), Eliphelet (third). The ordinal markers (firstborn, second, third) appear here and at the start of the chapter (v1&ndash;2), framing the whole with ordinal register at both ends. Eliphelet (<em>ʾelyepelet</em>, &lsquo;God is deliverance/escape&rsquo;) is a common name among David&rsquo;s sons (2 Sam 5:16) and warriors (2 Sam 23:34), suggesting its currency across social levels in Benjaminite-Judahite society.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Ulam&rsquo;s sons are &ldquo;mighty warriors, skilled archers (<em>dōrᵉkê qešet</em>), with many sons and grandsons &mdash; one hundred and fifty in all.&rdquo; Benjamin was the tribe of the skilled bowman (Judg 20:16: 700 left-handed slingers; 1 Chr 12:2: Benjaminite ambidextrous archers who joined David). The final note &ldquo;all these were of the sons of Benjamin&rdquo; closes ch8 and the entire two-chapter tribal survey (ch7&ndash;8) by re-anchoring the extended Saulide genealogy in its tribal identity. The closing formula &ldquo;one hundred and fifty&rdquo; descendants for Ulam alone demonstrates the Saulide family&rsquo;s demographic vitality into the post-exilic period.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('original', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRONICLES)
    save_comm('original', '1chronicles', existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in CHRONICLES.values())
    print(f'1 Chronicles 7-8 original fill: {total} verses written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
